;;; 01-forge-preflight-and-fire.slat — SRE Manual · Chapter 01 · Forge
;;;
;;; Runbook for firing Motoi training via Forge. Codifies the preflight
;;; rule that prevents two known-crash failure modes: empty pairs and
;;; over-length pairs. Added 2026-07-19 after Mk 1's first fire crashed
;;; twice on those exact modes.
;;;
;;; Read this before firing training. Do the preflight. Never skip.

(dialect :applies ("motoi-eng") :note "SRE Manual — Forge pre-flight + fire chapter.")

(chapter
  :number   "01"
  :title    "Forge: preflight the corpus, then fire"
  :book     "SRE Manual"
  :written  "2026-07-19"
  :audience ("sre" "training-pipeline" "engineering" "human-operator")
  :training-eligible #t
  :confidentiality  "internal-eng")

;; ═════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
;; § 1 — What this chapter is
;; ═════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
;;
;; Forge is the training harness (mlx_lm + wrappers) that fires SFT +
;; LoRA runs on Motoi and Sakura variants. This chapter is the SRE
;; runbook for what to do BEFORE, DURING, and AFTER a fire.
;;
;; The single most load-bearing rule: PREFLIGHT THE CORPUS BEFORE YOU
;; FIRE. Two failure modes will crash mlx_lm within 30 seconds of fire
;; if the corpus is dirty. Both are trivially detected by a linear
;; pass over the JSONL. Skipping preflight burns time you do not have.

;; ═════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
;; § 2 — The two crash modes (why preflight exists)
;; ═════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
;;
;; Mode 1 — empty pair.
;;
;;   Any JSONL row where `messages[0].content` or `messages[1].content`
;;   is empty (or missing) causes mlx_lm's `loss_value_and_grad` to
;;   receive an empty batch. The gradient call fails with:
;;
;;     ValueError: [grad] Must specify at least one argument.
;;
;;   You will see this at iter 1-10. The whole run dies. All Forge
;;   spinup time is wasted. Mk 1's first fire hit this on 2026-07-19
;;   at 22:15 UTC — 40 empty pairs in the base corpus caused it.
;;
;; Mode 2 — over-length pair.
;;
;;   Any JSONL row whose (user + assistant) content exceeds the
;;   model's `max_seq_length` (default 4,096 tokens ≈ 16,000 chars)
;;   gets silently truncated by mlx_lm. If truncation lops off the
;;   entire assistant reply, the effective content is empty, and the
;;   run dies with the same grad error above.
;;
;;   Mk 1's second fire hit this on 2026-07-19 at 22:19 UTC — 269
;;   book-chapter pairs up to 122k chars each. Same crash, different
;;   root cause.
;;
;; Both are trivially avoided by walking the corpus before firing.

;; ═════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
;; § 3 — The preflight rule (mandatory)
;; ═════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
;;
;; Every JSONL row must satisfy ALL of:
;;
;;   1. Parses as valid JSON (no truncated / malformed lines).
;;   2. Has a `messages` field with ≥ 2 entries.
;;   3. `messages[0].content` (user) — non-empty when stripped, ≥ 3 chars.
;;   4. `messages[1].content` (assistant) — non-empty when stripped, ≥ 5 chars.
;;   5. Combined length of user + assistant ≤ ~12,000 chars.
;;      (Safe headroom below the 4,096-token max_seq_length ≈ 16,000 chars.
;;       Change the threshold if max_seq_length changes.)
;;
;; If any row fails ANY of the five, the corpus is dirty. Do not fire.
;; Filter the offending rows, re-preflight, then fire.

;; ═════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
;; § 4 — The preflight script
;; ═════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
;;
;; Reference implementation:
;;   ~/code/motoi-scheme/scripts/corpus-preflight.py
;;
;; Usage:
;;   python3 scripts/corpus-preflight.py <corpus-dir>
;;   python3 scripts/corpus-preflight.py <corpus-dir> --max-chars 12000
;;
;; The script exits 0 on pass, non-zero on fail. Wire it into
;; forge-fire.sh (or into your pre-fire tick-card) so that firing
;; without a passing preflight is impossible.
;;
;; Reports per-file: rows total, rows OK, and per-issue counts
;; (empty / malformed / huge / short) with line numbers of first 5
;; offenders per class.

;; ═════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
;; § 5 — The pre-fire ritual (order of operations)
;; ═════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
;;
;;   0.  You have a corpus dir (usually `~/.forge/corpus/motoi-<gen>/`).
;;       Train/valid/heldout JSONLs are present. If not, fold first
;;       (scripts/fold-training-corpus.py).
;;
;;   1.  RUN PREFLIGHT.
;;         python3 ~/code/motoi-scheme/scripts/corpus-preflight.py \
;;             ~/.forge/corpus/motoi-<gen>/
;;
;;       If exit non-zero: STOP. Filter offending rows, save, re-preflight.
;;
;;   2.  VERIFY the mlx-lora-config.yaml matches what you intend.
;;       Specifically the seven checks:
;;         · model = "Qwen/Qwen2.5-Coder-1.5B-Instruct"
;;         · data = /Users/alfred/.forge/corpus/motoi-<gen>
;;         · seed = next odd prime in rotation
;;         · iters = ceil(train_rows × epochs / effective_batch)
;;         · lr_schedule.arguments = [1e-4, iters, 1e-5]
;;         · lora_parameters.rank = 128 (NO `keys` field — mlx_lm doesn't
;;           accept it; adding it silently produces 0% trainable params)
;;         · adapter_path = /Users/alfred/.forge/runs/motoi-<gen>/adapter
;;
;;   3.  FIRE.
;;         bash ~/code/forge/scripts/forge-fire.sh \
;;             ~/.forge/projects/motoi-<gen>/mlx-lora-config.yaml \
;;             motoi-<gen>
;;
;;       forge-fire.sh writes:
;;         · pid file at ~/.forge/runs/motoi-<gen>/pid
;;         · train.log at ~/.forge/runs/motoi-<gen>/train.log
;;         · train.cfg symlink (Forge UI reads iter target from here)
;;         · INITIAL FIRE banner in train.log (Forge lineage endpoint)
;;
;;   4.  VERIFY IT'S ALIVE.
;;         · tail -20 train.log — should see "Trainable parameters: X%"
;;           where X > 0. If X = 0, LoRA is not attached. Kill, fix config.
;;         · Iter 1 val loss should be a finite number (3-4 for Motoi 1.5B).
;;         · After a few minutes, iter counter should advance.
;;         · ps -p $(cat pid) confirms process is running.
;;
;;   5.  MONITOR.
;;         · Every save_every iters (default 500), a checkpoint lands.
;;         · Val loss should trend down over the run.
;;         · Peak memory should stabilize; if it grows unboundedly, kill.

;; ═════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
;; § 6 — Known-good iter arithmetic
;; ═════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
;;
;;   train_rows          = wc -l train.jsonl (POST-preflight, POST-filter)
;;   epochs              = 3 (Grand Weave doctrine)
;;   batch_size          = 1
;;   grad_accumulation   = 4
;;   effective_batch     = batch_size × grad_accumulation = 4
;;   iters               = ceil(train_rows × epochs / effective_batch)
;;   warmup              = ceil(iters × 0.05)  (5% warmup)
;;   lr_schedule args    = [peak_lr, iters, min_lr] = [1e-4, iters, 1e-5]
;;
;; Motoi Mk 1 (2026-07-19):
;;   train_rows = 109,393 (v8 base 103,815 + Mk 1 new 6,046 - filter 468)
;;   iters      = 82,045
;;   warmup     = 4,102
;;   wall clock estimate: ~5-6 h on M2 Max at ~4 it/sec

;; ═════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
;; § 7 — Odd-prime seed rotation
;; ═════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
;;
;; Grand Weave doctrine: use an odd prime seed for each generation. The
;; rotation avoids Adam-optimizer resonance events that even seeds have
;; been observed to produce.
;;
;;   v5  = 41
;;   v6  = 43
;;   v6-polish = 47
;;   v7  = 53   (Motoi 4.5)
;;   v8  = 61   (Motoi 5.0)
;;   Mk 1 = 67  (this run — 2026-07-19)
;;   next  = 71 (Mk 2, when you fire it)
;;   then  = 73, 79, 83, …
;;
;; Keep incrementing. Do not reuse a seed within the same lineage.

;; ═════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
;; § 8 — Config traps (real ones we hit)
;; ═════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
;;
;; Trap 1 — `lora_parameters.keys` field.
;;   Adding `keys: ["q_proj", ...]` to lora_parameters silently produces
;;   `Trainable parameters: 0.000%`. mlx_lm 0.x does not accept this
;;   field in its lora_parameters schema. Symptom: run starts, val loss
;;   computes normally at iter 1, but iter 10 either has zero loss
;;   delta or crashes with the grad error.
;;   Fix: remove the `keys` field. mlx_lm defaults to attaching LoRA
;;   to all attention projections, which is what we want anyway.
;;
;; Trap 2 — `num_layers: -1` interpretation.
;;   -1 means "all layers." Positive integer = last N layers only.
;;   For full LoRA, leave -1.
;;
;; Trap 3 — resume-from field.
;;   For fresh training (LIMO doctrine), do NOT set resume-from. If it's
;;   in the config from an earlier run, delete it or the model resumes
;;   from prior adapters and the Grand Weave assumption of "trained from
;;   base" breaks.
;;
;; Trap 4 — max_seq_length vs preflight threshold.
;;   If max_seq_length in config differs from preflight's --max-chars,
;;   preflight will let through pairs that truncate at training time.
;;   Rule of thumb: --max-chars = max_seq_length × ~3 (chars per token).
;;   For max_seq_length = 4,096 → --max-chars = 12,000.

;; ═════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
;; § 9 — When to kill a run
;; ═════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
;;
;; Kill immediately (call PushNotification, then `kill $(cat pid)`):
;;
;;   · `Trainable parameters: 0.000%` in train.log after model load.
;;     Config is broken; every iter wastes time.
;;
;;   · Iter 1 val loss NaN or ∞. Model isn't loading; kill, investigate.
;;
;;   · Iter 1 val loss > 10. Something is very wrong with the corpus
;;     or the tokenizer alignment; investigate before continuing.
;;
;;   · Loss diverges (goes up over 200+ iters). Learning rate too high,
;;     or corpus has contradictory examples. Kill and iterate on data.
;;
;;   · Peak memory > 90% of system memory. OOM imminent.
;;
;; Kill deliberately (checkpoint first, then `kill $(cat pid)`):
;;
;;   · Val loss plateau for 1000+ iters. Model has learned all it can
;;     from this corpus. Checkpoint and stop.
;;
;;   · Alfred says stop. This overrides everything.

;; ═════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
;; § 10 — After the run: checkpoint discipline
;; ═════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
;;
;; save_every 500 means every 500 iters, an adapter checkpoint lands
;; at ~/.forge/runs/motoi-<gen>/adapter/{iter}_adapters.safetensors.
;;
;; Ship candidate: pick the checkpoint with best val loss. Symlink it
;; to `ship-candidate.safetensors` for eval.
;;
;; Branching for finishing-move experiments (per Alfred's 2026-07-19
;; direction): the final SFT checkpoint is the branching point. From
;; that same checkpoint, apply different finishing moves in separate
;; runs — the checkpoint stays the base each time. Compare reveals
;; across variants; pick the winning finishing move.

;; ═════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
;; End of chapter 01.
;; ═════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
